# Dependency Management Rules

## Rule Name
dependency_management

## Description
Standards for managing dependencies and imports to prevent common development issues

## Dependencies
- Always verify dependencies are installed before importing
- Check package.json for correct versions
- Use consistent import patterns

## Import Rules
- Verify component libraries are properly installed
- Check import paths match actual file structure
- Use absolute imports with proper aliases when configured
- Fallback to relative imports if alias setup fails

## Common Issues Prevention
- ShadCN/ui: Ensure components are installed via CLI before importing
- MUI: Verify @mui/material and @emotion packages are installed
- React Router: Check react-router-dom is in dependencies
- TypeScript: Ensure @types packages are installed for external libraries

## File Structure Verification
- Check src/components/ui/ exists before importing ShadCN components
- Verify src/lib/ exists for utility functions
- Ensure page components are in correct directories
- Validate import paths match actual file locations

## Troubleshooting Steps
1. Check package.json for missing dependencies
2. Verify file structure matches import statements
3. Run yarn install to ensure all packages are properly linked
4. Check for typos in import paths
5. Verify component library initialization completed successfully

## Examples
```typescript
// Good: Verify dependency exists first
import { Button } from '@mui/material'; // @mui/material in package.json

// Bad: Importing from non-existent path
import { Button } from '@/components/ui/button'; // src/components/ui/button.tsx doesn't exist

// Good: Check file exists before importing
import NavigationBar from './components/NavigationBar'; // Relative import, file exists
```

## Notes
- Always install dependencies before importing components
- Use yarn add for adding new packages
- Check terminal output for installation success
- Verify file structure after component library initialization
